<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="eceb7bfc-fc6c-5628-a798-65aaf6827750" activityNameId="c7a09cc3-84fb-4d3d-a7b4-889fed5ce18a" parentActivityId="01871969-f0d0-4b3d-898f-fe27012fa628" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">dimethyl malonate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> DMM</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> malonic acid</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> C5H8O4</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> dimethylester</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Propanedioic acid</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with dimethyl malonate being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of dimethyl malonate.The production pathway is based on hydrogen cyanide and chloroacetic acid; the intermediate cyanoacetic acid is simultaneously saponified and esterified in the presence of a large excess of mineral acid and alcohol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dimethyl malonate (C5H8O4 | DMM) is a colorless organic liquids with an ester like odor. Dimethyl malonate is sparingly soluble in water (1 g/50 mL), but miscible in all portions with diethyl ether and ethanol. At room temperature, malonates and alcoholic solutions thereof exist almost exclusively in the keto form. Dimethyl malonates are widely used for the production of vitamins, pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, fragrances, and dyes. In the agrochemical field, malonates are mainly used for the production of two classes of herbicides: the cyclohexanedione-type and the sulfonylurea herbicides. The synthesis of the 1,3-cyclohexanedione herbicides commences with a Michael addition of malonates to 1-substituted but-1-en-3-ones followed by ring closure and subsequent decarboxylation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Malonates are produced either by cobalt-catalyzed alkoxycarbonylation of chloroacetates with carbon monoxide in the presence of alcohol or by hydrolysis of cyanoacetic acid followed by esterification with the respective alcohol, i.e., the carbon monoxide and hydrogen cyanide processs, repsectively. For this dataset the production of dimethyl malonate by means of the hydrogen cyanide process is considered.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Reactions:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Cl-CH2-COONa + NaCN → NC-CH-COONa + NaCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">NC-CH-COONa + 2CH4O + HCl → C5H8O4 + NH3 + NaCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Kim S., Overcash M.: Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate-to-gate information for life cycle as-sessment. In: Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology vol. 78, no. 9: 995-1005(11). 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Harald Strittmatter, Stefan Hildbrand, Peter Pollak: Malonic Acid and Derivatives. Published online: 2007. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a16_063.pub2</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The production of dimethyl malonate is based on hydrogen cyanide and chloroacetic acid, where the intermediate cyanoacetic acid is simultaneously saponified and esterified in the presence of a large excess of mineral acid and alcohol.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reactions:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Cl-CH2-COONa + NaCN → NC-CH-COONa + NaCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">NC-CH-COONa + 2CH4O + HCl → C5H8O4 + NH3 + NaCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">A solution of sodium cyanide (ca. 25 %) in water is heated to 65 – 70 °C in a stainless steel reaction vessel. An aqueous solution of sodium chloroacetate is then added slowly with stirring; the temperature must not exceed 90 °C. Stirring is maintained at this temperature for an hour. Particular care must be taken to ensure that the hydrogen cyanide, which is formed continuously in small amounts, is trapped and neutralized. The solution of sodium cyanoacetate is concentrated by evaporation under vacuum and then transferred to a glass-lined reaction vessel for hydrolysis of the cyano group and esterification. The alcohol and mineral acid (weight ratio 1:2 to 1:3) are introduced in such a manner that the temperature does not rise above 60 – 80 °C. For each mol of ester, ca. 1.2 mol of alcohol is added. Hydrochloric acid, which is formed as byproduct from unreacted chloroacetic acid, is fed into an absorption column. After the addition of acid and alcohol is complete, the mixture is heated at reflux for 6 – 8 h, whereby the intermediate malonic acid ester monoamide is hydrolyzed to a dialkyl malonate. The pure ester is obtained from the mixture of crude esters by extraction with benzene, toluene, or xylene. The organic phase is washed with dilute sodium hydroxide to remove small amounts of the monoester. The diester is then separated from solvent by distillation at atmospheric pressure, and the malonic ester obtained by distillation under vacuum as a colourless liquid with a minimum assay of 99 % (gas chromatography). The aqueous phase contains considerable amounts of mineral acid and salts and must be treated before being fed to the waste treatment plant. The process is suitable for both the dimethyl and diethyl esters.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Although a relatively simple plant is sufficient for the reaction itself, a sizeable investment is required for treatment of the wastewater and exhaust gas.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">The yield based on sodium chloroacetate is 75 – 85 %. Various low molecular mass hydrocarbons, some of them partially chlorinated, are formed as byproducts. In this dataset, an overal yield of 85% was assumed (i.e., an average 92% yield for each reaction step). </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Kim S., Overcash M.: Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate-to-gate information for life cycle as-sessment. In: Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology vol. 78, no. 9: 995-1005(11). 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Harald Strittmatter, Stefan Hildbrand, Peter Pollak: Malonic Acid and Derivatives. Published online: 2007. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a16_063.pub2</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2003-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2003) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
